Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) showed the morphology and shape of the cys-GQDs and its InPc conjugates (Fig. 2
                        ). While the TEM image for the cys-GQDs (Fig. 2a) showed the graphene quantum dots as spherical and monodispersed, InPc@cys-GQDs showed the cluster form because of the π-π interaction between InPc complex and adjacent quantum dots as a result of aggregation [43]. The aggregation is always possible for the phthalocyanines through π- π stacking [44], hence the interaction of the phthalocyanines with adjacent GQDs rich in π electrons is common in this manner resulting in cluster image. (See Fig. 3
                        ).

Fluorescence quantum yield (ΦF) measures how efficiently a molecule emits light after absorbing it. A low ΦF is important for photodynamic therapy and sono-photodynamic therapy because it indicates that the sensitizer can effectively produce reactive oxygen species for cancer treatment. Thus, assessing ΦF is crucial for identifying suitable sensitizers in these therapies [50]. In this study, fluorescence measurement was made with the solution of synthesized phthalocyanine compounds prepared in DMSO at approximately 0.5 absorbance for emission and the solution was additionally diluted for excitation analysis. Fig. 7
                         shows the absorption, fluorescence excitation and emission spectra of InPc. The fluorescence quantum yield of InPc in DMSO was calculated to be ΦF = 0.024 (Table 1
                        ) and it is lower than unsubstituted ZnPc (ΦF = 0.20) we used as a standard [51]. The low fluorescence quantum yield results in increased intersystem crossing and therefore higher levels of singlet oxygen generation.
